ason the project produces profit is because the COST of the plant, and the MORTGAGE to pay for it (which is the vast bulk of atomic costs) was simply &quot;stranded&quot; on the citizens of Canada.<br>
<br>
Counting the FULL expense, the system is a huge money burning rat-hole.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> STRANDED DEBT<br>
<br>
At the time of its dissolution on April 1, 1999, Ontario Hydro had a debt of $38 billion. Hydro’s nuclear plants were very expensive to build and generated much less revenue than expected due to poor performance, so it was clear that they would not be viable under a fair competitive system. They were thus said to be 'stranded assets’ and the estimated debt that they could not carry was termed 'stranded debt’.<br>
<br>
In the April 1999 accounting, OPG was left with only a $3.4 billion debt to service, and Hydro One, only $4.8 billion. The Stranded Debt was estimated at $21 billion, of which $8 billion will be paid by all electricity consumers through a “Competition Transition Charge”. Ominously, the stranded debt can still be increased, and OPG has since increased its debt.<br>
<br>
By removing most nuclear debt from OPG, the stranded debt allocation has acted as a massive bailout for the nuclear plants, in effect providing a subsidy for nuclear rehabilitation. In particular, the $1.3 billion cost of re-starting the four old Pickering A reactors. In the case of Bruce Power, the elimination of the need to service the multi-billion dollar debt for the Bruce reactors is providing a huge subsidy to a private corporation.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
