them profitable? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 134<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/16/02 9:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Bruce-reactor profit forecast raised $1 billion.</span><hr size=1> The TRIGA is profitable to its MANUFACTURER, not the user.<br>
A fleet of Lexus school buses would be very profitable to the Lexus company but, a disaster for the bus fleet trying to bid out its services.<br>
<br>
As to strict regulations adding to the cost.. YES, that is the whole point. Each of these machines contain the equivalent of more than a thousand atomic bombs worth of fallout being contained in a core that would reach 5,000 degrees if not constantly cooled. A major release would kill up to a range of 100,000 or so people and contaminate thousands of square miles. <br>
<br>
Millions of people live within just a few miles of a reactor. The expense of dealing with such an incredibly hazardous machine requires vast sums of material and money. <br>
<br>
The failed economics of atomic energy is imposed by the needs of the TECHNOLOGY. <br>
<br>
Why does an airliner cost so much money? Because it MUST in order to be safe. Exactly the same logic holds true for atomic plants, but on a vaster scale.<br>
<br>
Every time the industry tried to cut corners, like the ridiculous pressure suppression containments of GE boiling water reactors (a failure in itself), it jumps out and bites you.<br>
<br>
As an aside, coal plants are also economic failures, more so if proper pollution controls are used. <br>
<br>
Neither technology is central anymore.<br>
 yale<br>
