<br>
In the US, there is a huge potential for mid-head and low-head hydo capacity backfit at EXISTING non-power producing dams (thus resulting in no additional environmental costs). Overcapacity and dirt cheap natural gas power plants discourage financing these projects.<br>
<br>
Wind, the fastest growing energy source, has been barely utilized. Thosands of gigawatts of potential resources exist.<br>
<br>
Hydrogen has an incredible future. Its use (the Hydrogen Economy) will transform the world. The problem is that it is not a primary energy source. It is produced using energy from another source. Wind, photovoltaic, hydro, nuclear fission, fusion, whatever is used to split water. The key is a power source cheap enuff to split water cheaply. Hydro and wind currently are the best bets but they are still too expensive.<br>
<br>
Some more exotic source like gene modified algae I think will soon come on line as a cheap hydrogen source.<br>
